{{More footnotes|date=January 2017}} {{Infobox product | title = Tillie the All-Time Teller | image = Tillie_the_All-Time_Teller.jpeg | alt = | caption = A screenshot of an advertisement for Tillie the All-Time Teller | type = [[Automated teller machine]] | inventor = | launch year = {{start date|1974}} | company = [[First National Bank of Atlanta]] | available = Discontinued | current supplier = | last production = | models = | url = | notes = }}
'''Tillie the All-Time Teller''' was one of the first [[Automated teller machine|ATM]]s,<ref name=news>{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Wayde|title=The automatic bank tellers are here|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1734&dat=19760515&id=gJUbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=glEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4482,1397894&safe=on&hl=en|accessdate=19 August 2015|agency=N.Y. Times News Service|publisher=The Dispatch|date=May 19, 1976}}</ref> run by the [[First National Bank of Atlanta]] and considered to be one of the most successful ATMs in the banking industry. Tillie the All-Time Teller had a picture of a smiling blonde girl on the front of the machine to suggest it was user-friendly, had an apparent personality,<ref name=digest>{{cite book|title=Computer Digest, Volumes 9-11|date=1974|publisher=American Data Processing|page=406|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WtgaAQAAMAAJ&q=Tillie+the+All-Time+Teller&dq=Tillie+the+All-Time+Teller|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> and could greet people by name.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grayson|first1=Richard|title=University Drive|date=February 13, 2015|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=1312917660|page=49|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=80RpCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=tillie+the+all+time+teller#v=onepage&q=tillie%20the%20all%20time%20teller&f=false|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> Many banks hired women dressed as this person to show their customers how to use Tillie the All-Time Teller.
==History== It was introduced by the [[First National Bank of Atlanta]] on May 15, 1974. It started out at only eleven locations.<ref>{{cite web|title=On May 15, 1974First National Bank of Atlanta (now part of Wells Fargo) introduced eleven new automated teller machines to customers.|url=https://plus.google.com/+wellsfargo/posts/ALbSJDXxEy8|website=Google+|publisher=Wells Fargo|accessdate=20 August 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422235006/https://plus.google.com/+wellsfargo/posts/ALbSJDXxEy8|archivedate=22 April 2016|df=}}</ref> They were in commerce starting May 20, 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tsdrsec.uspto.gov/ts/cd/casedoc/sn73030081/ORC20051121153756/download.pdf|title=Tillie the Alltime Teller|publisher=United States Patent Office|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref> Starting 1977, other banks purchased rights to use Tillie the All-Time Teller as their ATM system. By March 21, 1981, they were available at 70 locations,<ref>{{cite news|title=3. Hour Convenience Of Tillie The Alltime Teller At 70 Locations|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19810329&id=NGhRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dgYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1812,6777209&hl=en|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref> including on a college campus.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Fact, You're Going to Love Me 24 Hours a Day, 365 Days a Year|url=https://d.lib.ncsu.edu/ocr/technician-v60n22-1979-10-17/technician-v60n22-1979-10-17.txt}}</ref> On October 15, 2013, [[Susan Bennett]] revealed that she played the voice for Tillie the All-Time Teller, noting that she "started [her] life as a machine quite young."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ravitz|first1=Jennifer|title='I'm the original voice of Siri'|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/10/04/tech/mobile/bennett-siri-iphone-voice|accessdate=15 August 2015|publisher=CNN|date=October 15, 2013}}</ref>
==Appearance== Tillie the All-Time Teller machines were red and gold to make them look more attractive.<ref name=digest /> On the bottom left was the place to enter an "access card," which featured a cartoon character.<ref name=digest /> Above that was a place to enter a "secret code" that the customer chose.<ref name=digest /> On the bottom center was a picture of a cartoon blonde girl with china-blue eyes<ref name=news /> and a red hat. Above that was the place it handed out cash and coins. On the top right was the place to enter a desired amount of money.
==How it worked== [[File:Tillie the All-Time Teller appearence.jpeg|thumb|A diagram showing the steps to using Tillie the All-Time Teller]]
Customers could use Tillie the All-Time Teller by following these steps: # Inserting an "Alltime Tellercard" # Following instructions presented on its TV screen # Entering a "secret code" and entering a desired amount of money on the "money keyboard" ($200 was the limit) # The machine would automatically hand out the desired amount of money. # Entering a transaction envelope into the deposit slot
==Advertising== There were a variety of advertisements made by the [[First National Bank of Atlanta]] in order to promote Tillie the All-Time Teller. These include:<!--all three cited in the "Bibliography" section.--> * In one of the advertisements, a blonde woman that wore a red and white polka-dotted dress sang "I'm Tillie the All-Time Teller, I work for First National Bank" while standing beside the machine. * In another advertisement, a balding, middle-aged man approached the machine singing "If You Knew Tillie" to the tune of "[[If You Knew Susie]]." The song went like this: {{quote|<poem>Oh, if you knew Tillie like I know Tillie Oh, oh, oh, what a girl! She works to please me, to make life easy Oh, oh, she makes my banking smooth and breezy Day or nighttime, I don’t care When I need money, I know my all-time teller’s there! If you knew Tillie, like I know Tillie Oh, oh, oh!</poem>}} * For Tillie the All-Time Teller's third anniversary, the machine was featured in an advertisement where they sang "She's a Jolly Good Teller." It originally aired on KSEL-TV and [[KAMC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texasarchive.org/library/index.php?title=Dub_Rogers_-_KLBK_Archival_Footage%2C_no._9_-_American_State_Bank|title=Dub Rogers - KLBK Archival Footage, no. 9 - American State Bank|work=Texas Archive of the Moving Image}}</ref>
==In popular culture== The word "Tillie" has become a slang to describe any ATM.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Billips|first1=Mike|title=Since '78, Atlanta lost banks, but not economic power|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/1998/06/15/focus8.html|website=Atlanta Business Chronicle|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref>
